The camera can automatically select the aperture based on the current environment. If you choose to adjust the aperture manually, remember that the smaller its value, the more light hits the sensor.

When LOG is on, flexibly control exposure and dynamic range by adjusting the exposure index (EI). With higher EI, the camera captures more light, showing more detail in the highlights, while the inverse is true for shadows.

"Automatic shutter speed is determined by the camera's light meter. When you select shutter speed manually, remember that the longer the shutter is open, the more light gets on the sensor, making your image brighter."
This feature allows you to compensate exposure when you want your image to be brighter or darker than the meter suggests.
You can focus both manually and automatically. The greater focus value you select on the slider, the farther from the lens the in-focus area will be.

ISO values can be determined automatically by the light meter. You can also change the value manually. Remember that higher ISO makes your camera more sensitive to light, but brings more digital noise into your image.
This format records video with logarithmic function applied to the exposure curve in order to capture more details in highlights and shadows, giving you more options in post-processing.
Turn on LOG to import customized LUTs for video previews. Videos will be recorded in LOG files.

Contrast is used to adjust the difference between light and dark areas in a photo. Increasing the contrast will make the difference between light and dark more obvious, while lowering the contrast will make the picture look softer.
Hue allows you to make an image appear colder or warmer.

Saturation allows you to control the depth and intensity of colors, adjusting contrast brings out or minimizes the difference between light and dark, and sharpness renders the details along the outlines.

Saturation refers to the purity of colors in a photo. Increasing saturation makes an image more vivid, decreasing it can make an image more elegant and understated, and reducing saturation to zero will make the image black and white.
Sharpness affects how clear the edges of objects in the photo are. Increasing the sharpness makes the photo clearer, while reducing sharpness makes images softer and more delicate.

resources.string: Volume adjustment: The volume of the recorded audio is adjusted according to the current scene where ambient sounds may be too loud or too quiet.
Omni-directional: Sound from all directions is equalized to create a balanced audio experience for the entire scene.
Rear: This mode focuses on sound behind the person holding the camera and reduces sound from other directions.
Trajectory: This mode allows you to record clear sound from in front of and behind the person holding the camera by attenuating the sound to the left and right.
Forward: This mode focuses on sound in front of the person holding the camera and reduces sound from other directions.
Source zoom: Focuses on sound within the viewfinder range and reduces sound from other directions.
